PSEUDOCODE
==========

Enable clocks for GPIOA and TIM2
Configure PA5 as Alternate Function (TIM2_CH1)
Configure TIM2 in PWM mode 1 on Channel 1:
    PSC  -> scale 16MHz to 1MHz (1 tick = 1µs)
    ARR  -> 1000 - 1 (PWM period = 1ms -> 1kHz frequency)
    CCR1 -> duty cycle value (0 to ARR)
    Set PWM Mode 1, enable preload on CCR1
    Enable channel output
    Enable TIM2 counter

Loop forever:
    Set CCR1 = 250  -> 25% duty cycle  (dim)
    wait 2 seconds
    Set CCR1 = 500  -> 50% duty cycle  (medium)
    wait 2 seconds
    Set CCR1 = 950  -> 95% duty cycle  (bright)
    wait 2 seconds

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIN MAP
=======

PA5   =>  TIM2_CH1 (Alternate Function 2) - PWM output to onboard LED

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY REGISTERS
=============

GPIOA (General-Purpose Input/Output Port A)
|--------------|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register     | Field               | Description                                                                          |
|--------------|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| GPIOA->MODER | bits[11:10] for PA5 | 10 = Alternate Function mode. Pin is now controlled by the peripheral, not ODR/BSRR. |
| GPIOA->AFRL  | bits[23:20] for PA5 | Selects which alternate function. AF2 = 0010 = TIM2_CH1 on PA5.                      |
|--------------|---------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

TIM2 (General-Purpose Timer)
|-------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Register    | Field          | Description                                                                                              |
|-------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| TIM2->CCMR1 | bits[6:4] OC1M | Output Compare Mode for CH1. 110 = PWM Mode 1: output HIGH while CNT < CCR1, LOW otherwise.              |
| TIM2->CCMR1 | bit3     OC1PE | Output Compare Preload Enable. CCR1 writes buffer until next update event. Prevents glitches mid-period. |
| TIM2->CCR1  | bits[31:0]     | Capture/Compare Register 1. Holds the duty cycle threshold. CNT < CCR1 => pin HIGH.                      |
| TIM2->CCER  | bit0      CC1E | Capture/Compare 1 Output Enable. Actually connects the PWM signal to the pin.                            |
| TIM2->CR1   | bit7      ARPE | Auto-Reload Preload Enable. Buffers ARR writes. Set this when changing frequency on the fly.             |
|-------------|----------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

KEY CONCEPTS
============

What is PWM?
PWM (Pulse Width Modulation) is a technique where we rapidly switch a digital
output ON and OFF at a fixed frequency, but vary how long it stays ON vs
OFF. Even though the signal is always either 0V or 3.3V, the average voltage
perceived by a load (motor, LED, etc.) depends on that ratio.

 HIGH     ____      ____      ____
         |    |    |    |    |    |
 LOW   __|    |____|    |____|    |____     50% duty -> avg 1.65V


 HIGH     ______    ______    ______
         |      |  |      |  |      |
 LOW   __|      |__|      |__|      |__     75% duty -> avg 2.47V

PWM on STM32 is generated entirely by a hardware timer, our CPU doesn't toggle
the pin manually. The timer has an internal counter register (CNT) that counts
up (or down) on every tick of a clock.

Capture/Compare Register(CCR) is the heart of PWM. Each timer channel has its
own CCR. The timer hardware continuously compares the running CNT value against
CCR. So, CCR directly controls how long the signal stays high within each period
(this is the duty cycle). To change duty cycle at runtime, we just write a new
value to CCR.

Let's go through an example to better understand:
ARR = 999
PSC = 15
CCR = 300 (30% duty)

One Cycle of PWM (CNT goes from 0 to 999)
The first 300 ticks, the pin-state is HIGH and the rest of the 700 ticks, the
pin-state is LOW. Signal goes HIGH and LOW only once per cycle.

The PWM Frequency is 1kHz. It means that 1000 such cycles happen per second. So
this HIGH-LOW pattern repeats 1000 times every second.

Our load (LED) sees this pin voltage over time.
 HIGH     __       __       __
         |  |     |  |     |  |
 LOW   __|  |_____|  |_____|  |_____     30% duty -> avg 0.99V

The Load physically cannot react fast enough to the individual ON/OFF switching
at 1kHz. So, it sees a steady ~0.99V effectively.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

COMMON MISTAKES AND DEBUG TIPS
==============================

* Forgetting to set AFRL. Setting MODER = 10 (AF mode) without configuring AFRL
  leaves the pin connected to AF0 by default, which is usually nothing or
  SWD. The LED will not respond at all. Always set both MODER and AFRL together.

* CCR1 > ARR gives 100% but check our intent. If CCR1 >= ARR, the output stays
  permanently HIGH (100% duty). If CCR1 = 0, output stays permanently LOW (0%
  duty). Neither is wrong, but know the boundary behavior. pwm_set_duty() clamps
  at PWM_ARR for safety.

* OC1PE not set. CCR1 updates cause glitches, without preload enabled on CCR1,
  writing a new duty cycle takes effect immediately mid-period, which can
  produce a runt pulse. With OC1PE = 1, the new value loads cleanly at the next
  update event (start of next period).

* PA5 still in output mode from a previous program. If we're flashing over
  Program 1(LED Blinking) without a full reset, MODER might still be 01
  (output). Always clear MODER bits before setting the new mode, which the code
  does explicitly.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

EXTRA NOTES
===========

* PWM frequency vs resolution trade-off. Here we use PSC=15 (1MHz clock) and
  ARR=999 (1kHz PWM). This gives 1000 steps of duty cycle resolution (0–999). If
  we increase frequency to 10kHz (ARR=99), we only get 100 steps of
  resolution. If we decrease to 100Hz (ARR=9999), we get 10000 steps but visible
  flicker on some LEDs. Choose based on what matters for the application.

* TIM2 now runs freely in the background, Unlike Program 4 where TIM2 was
  started and stopped for each delay, here it runs continuously and the hardware
  PWM signal is generated entirely without CPU involvement. The CPU only touches
  CCR1 to change duty, the waveform itself is hardware-generated. This is the
  power of output compare mode.

* This is the foundation for next Program (Breathing LED). The breathing effect
  is simply calling pwm_set_duty() with a value that smoothly ramps up and down
  over time using the SysTick timebase. The PWM infrastructure built here stays
  identical, only the value fed into CCR1 changes.
